[1]
Date: Mon 10 Aug 2015
Source: New York Times [edited]
http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/nyregion/death-toll-from-legionnaires-disease-outbreak-in-bronx-rises-to-12.html?_r=0


An outbreak of legionnaires' disease in the South Bronx has claimed 2 more lives, bringing the death toll to 12, with a total of 113 people infected since early July, New York City officials said on Monday [10 Aug 2015].

The 2 deaths were the first to be reported since last week and served as a reminder that while the outbreak appears to have ebbed in recent days, the toll is still emerging. People can become sick by inhaling contaminated mist from a water source that contains the legionella bacteria, which cause the disease.

City health officials have said they believe they have traced the source of the outbreak to a group of 5 water-cooling towers in the South Bronx that initially tested positive for legionella. The towers are at Lincoln Medical and Mental Health Center; the Opera House Hotel; Concourse Plaza shopping mall; a Verizon office building; and Streamline Plastics Company. All of the sites have been treated and disinfected.

At least 5 more towers also tested positive in the last few days, but health officials have said they do not believe any of those five are responsible for the outbreak. Cooling towers are bulky structures on rooftops on modern buildings that help control hot and cold air in buildings.

The outbreak prompted city health officials to take the unprecedented step last week of ordering every building with a cooling tower in the city to inspect and disinfect it within two weeks. Investigators with the State Health Department and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention also have stepped in to help test and collect water samples from cooling towers in the Bronx.

[byline: Winnie Hu, Noah Remnick]

