[3]
Date: Tue 11 Aug 2015
Source: BBC [edited]
http://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-33856450


An outbreak of legionnaires' disease in New York - largest in the city's history - has left at least 12 people dead and health officials scrambling to contain the deadly bacteria. More than 100 cases have been reported in the South Bronx, one of the city's poorest neighbourhoods. Officials have traced the legionella bacteria to cooling towers in more than a dozen buildings.

The elderly are especially at risk from this form of pneumonia. All but one of the 12 victims were older than 40 years old and all of them had underlying health problems.

Cleaning crews have been dispatched across the Bronx to kill the bacteria. The disease is not transmitted person to person. It is primarily spread via air conditioning and similar systems.

New York Mayor Bill de Blasio has been criticised over the city's response to the outbreak. "We are dealing with a new set of realities we have never experienced that we have never encountered before in this city,'' New York Mayor Bill de Blasio said on Monday [10 Aug 2015].

The disease has a 10-day incubation period, which has caused a lag in the reporting of cases. But Mr de Blasio and New York health officials believe that there has not been a new case since 3 August.

The response has been muddled by a lack of coordination between city and state health officials. On Monday, New York Governor Andrew Cuomo and Mr de Blasio held duelling news conferences, at times offering conflicting information. The response to the outbreak is the latest in a series of incidents where the men - Democrats who claimed to be friends - have been at odds.

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of cases of legionnaires' disease and deaths continues to increase with now 113 cases and 12 deaths, even though the last of the 5 cooling towers suspected of being the source of this outbreak was remediated 9 days ago. However, even if all the sources have been eliminated, the number of legionnaires' disease cases could continue to rise over the next 5 days because the incubation period of legionnaires' disease is 2-14 days after exposure.

Legionellosis is commonly caused by inhalation of aerosols containing _Legionella pneumophila_. These aerosols are lightweight and remain suspended in air for prolonged periods of time to spread for considerable distances to involve people downwind from the contaminated source. The effect of wind direction and speed of contaminated plumes from cooling towers may influence the distribution of cases. A map of the South Bronx that shows the distribution of cases relative to the location of contaminated cooling towers can be found at [2] source URL http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/nyregion/death-toll-from-legionnaires-disease-outbreak-in-bronx-rises-to-12.html.

It is likely that the tests that city officials say they are awaiting to identify which of the cooling towers is responsible for the legionnaires' disease outbreak is genotyping strains isolated from patients and cooling towers. A match between the genotype of legionella strains isolated from a cooling tower and the genotype of strains isolated from any of the patients would identify that cooling tower as the source for those patients. - Mod.ML

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3573605,1581.]
